In the Q2 2026 landscape, ""Multi-Channel"" support—simply being present on multiple interfaces—is a commodity. Yellow.ai differentiates through ""Agentic Omnichannel Orchestration"", a capability that ensures state continuity and interaction logic across channels, enabling true asynchronous and synchronous multi-modality.

1.2.1 Consistent Experiences and Channel Specificity
The platform supports over 135+ distinct interaction channels, ranging from traditional web chat and mobile apps to proprietary enterprise messaging systems, SMS, WhatsApp, and Voice (PSTN/VoIP). To maximize application code reuse, Yellow.ai decouples the core conversational logic from the channel-specific presentation layer. A single ""Agent"" definition contains the business logic (e.g., ""Check Order Status""), while the platform’s channel adapters automatically render the output appropriately for the endpoint.   

For instance, a ""Menu Selection"" node in the flow builder will automatically render as a clickable carousel on Web Chat, a numbered list on WhatsApp, and a Text-to-Speech (TTS) prompt (""Press 1 for..."") on a voice call. This ""Write Once, Deploy Everywhere"" architecture significantly reduces maintenance overhead, as changes to the core logic propagate instantly across all active channels without requiring channel-specific code refactoring.

1.2.2 Simultaneous Multi-Modal Interactions (Interruption-Aware)
A critical advancement in the 2026 platform is the support for simultaneous multi-modal interactions, specifically the ability to interrupt a voice interaction with a digital one. Yellow.ai describes this as ""Interruption-Aware Duplex Orchestration"".   

Consider a customer service scenario: A user is on a voice call with an AI agent to discuss a billing dispute. The agent, recognizing that reading a complex table of charges via TTS would be poor UX, triggers a ""Digital Assist"" action. The platform sends a secure link via SMS or WhatsApp to the user’s smartphone. As the user opens the link and interacts with the visual interface (e.g., selecting a specific charge to dispute), the Voice Agent is aware of these actions in real-time via the User360 graph. The voice agent can then comment on the user's digital actions (""I see you've selected the charge from January 12th..."") without the user needing to verbalize their selection. This synchronization transforms the interaction from a disjointed multi-channel experience into a cohesive, multimodal session.

1.2.3 Omnichannel Deployment Statistics
Yellow.ai’s strategic focus on this capability is reflected in its deployment metrics. The platform powers large-scale omnichannel deployments where enterprise clients interact with customers on three or more channels simultaneously. The largest single omnichannel deployment to date supports interactions across Voice, WhatsApp, and Mobile App for a global financial institution, handling millions of concurrent sessions that leverage this cross-channel state awareness."																					
Personalized Customer Experiences	"How does the platform organize and store customer data to enable personalized experiences?
 
 If this data is synchronized with external systems, how does that synchronization process work?
 
 How is data accessed and used at runtime by the platform's bots?"	"In the administrator / developer demo:
 
  * Show how data that is useful for personalization can be gathered, managed and stored, and how it is accessed and used at runtime."	0	"Personalized Customer Experiences
The ""Personalization"" criterion is often interpreted as simple variable substitution (e.g., ""Hello, [Name]""). Yellow.ai redefines this through its ""User360"" architecture, also referred to as the ""User Graph"", which provides the AI with ""Episodic Memory.""

1.3.1 The User Graph vs. Session Context
Most conversational platforms maintain ""Session Context""—memory that lasts only as long as the chat window is open. Yellow.ai’s User Graph is persistent. It aggregates data from every interaction a user has ever had with the brand across all channels, creating a longitudinal view of the customer relationship.   

This ""Episodic Memory"" allows the agent to exhibit ""Historical Intimacy."" If a user contacts support, the agent does not merely ask ""How can I help you?""; it references the User Graph to see that the user called three days ago about a failed payment and expressed frustration (via sentiment analysis). The agent can opens with, ""Hi John, are you calling about the payment issue from Tuesday?"" This capability fundamentally shifts the user experience from transactional to relational.

1.3.2 Data Access and Runtime Synchronization
The User Graph is not a static database; it is a dynamic Customer Data Platform (CDP) component. At runtime, when an interaction initiates, the platform connects to external systems of record (CRMs like Salesforce, ERPs like SAP, or core banking systems) to fetch the latest attributes. This ""Priming"" process injects relevant user data into the agent's context window before the first token is generated.   

Crucially, the synchronization is bidirectional. As the agent learns new information during the conversation (e.g., the user has moved to a new address), it updates the User Graph. This update can trigger a write-back to the external CRM, ensuring that the enterprise’s central records are kept in sync with the unstructured data gathered by the AI. "																					
Agentic Framework	"How do developers define agentic plans for the agent and how are they executed?
 
 How do developers define tools, resources, state, and context for the agent, and how are they used at runtime?"	"Present the following slides:
 
  * A diagram slide of the agentic framework.
